    "\n",

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Creating Sample Data\n",
    "\n",
    "To verify the effectiveness of ARIMA models, we create synthetic data that includes a trend, seasonality (periodicity), and noise."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2026-02-26T11:45:08.552670Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2026-02-26T11:45:08.552316Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2026-02-26T11:45:24.263715Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2026-02-26T11:45:24.263206Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Plot size 1200x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Trend + Seasonality + Noise\n",
    "t0 = 0\n",
    "dt = 0.1\n",
    "duration = 30\n",
    "t = np.arange(0, duration, dt)\n",
    "n_samples = len(t)\n",
    "\n",
    "# 1. Linear Trend\n",
    "trend = 0.3 * t\n",
    "\n",
    "# 2. Periodic component (Sine)\n",
    "seasonality = 2.0 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * 0.2 * t)\n",
    "\n",
    "# 3. Noise\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "noise = np.random.normal(0, 0.8, n_samples)\n",
    "\n",
    "data = trend + seasonality + noise\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create TimeSeries object\n",
    "ts = TimeSeries(data, t0=t0, dt=dt, unit=\"V\", name=\"Sample Data\")\n",
    "\n",
    "ts.plot()\n",
    "plt.title(\"Original Data (Trend + Seasonality + Noise)\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. AR (AutoRegressive) Model\n",
    "\n",
    "The AR model assumes that the current value depends on past values.\n",
    "Use the `ts.ar(p)` method, where `p` is the order."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2026-02-26T11:45:24.292050Z",

     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Fit with order p=3\n",
    "model_ar = ts.ar(p=3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Display model summary\n",
    "# print(model_ar.summary())\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot results\n",
    "# forecast_steps specifies how many steps to forecast into the future\n",
    "model_ar.plot(forecast_steps=50, alpha=0.5)\n",
    "plt.title(\"AR(3) Model Forecast\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

    "## 6. Application in Gravitational Wave Data Analysis: Noise Removal (Whitening) with ARIMA\n",
    "\n",
    "In gravitational wave data analysis, a process called **whitening** is performed to extract burst signals or ringdown waveforms from stationary \"colored noise\".\n",
    "By training an ARIMA model as a predictive model for background noise and subtracting the predicted values from the measured values (taking residuals), it is possible to remove noise and enhance the signal."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 1: Generating Colored Noise and Injecting a Signal\n",
    "First, we create colored noise with strong low-frequency components (AR(1) process), and embed a weak signal (sine-Gaussian) that is difficult to distinguish otherwise.\n",
    "Note: We use \"strain\" as the unit, which is recognizable by Astropy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2026-02-26T11:48:31.861936Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2026-02-26T11:48:31.861823Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2026-02-26T11:48:31.968796Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2026-02-26T11:48:31.967986Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x400 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "from gwexpy.timeseries import TimeSeries\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def generate_mock_data(duration=10, fs=1024):\n",
    "    t = np.linspace(0, duration, int(duration * fs))\n",
    "\n",
    "    # 1. Background Noise (AR(1) process with strong autocorrelation)\n",
    "    np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "    white_noise = np.random.normal(0, 1, len(t))\n",
    "    colored_noise = np.zeros_like(white_noise)\n",
    "    for i in range(1, len(t)):\n",
    "        colored_noise[i] = 0.95 * colored_noise[i - 1] + white_noise[i]\n",
    "\n",
    "    # 2. Injected Signal (Sine-Gaussian)\n",
    "    center_time = 5.0\n",
    "    sig_freq = 50.0\n",
    "    width = 0.1\n",
    "    signal = (\n",
    "        2.0\n",
    "        * np.exp(-((t - center_time) ** 2) / (2 * width**2))\n",
    "        * np.sin(2 * np.pi * sig_freq * t)\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    data = colored_noise + signal\n",
    "    # Use a standard unit string that astropy/gwpy can recognize\n",
    "    return TimeSeries(data, t0=0, dt=1 / fs, unit=\"strain\", name=\"MockData\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "ts = generate_mock_data()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\n",
    "plt.plot(ts, color=\"gray\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"Original Noisy Data (Signal is hidden here)\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Time [s]\")\n",
    "plt.grid(True, linestyle=\":\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {

    "# We prioritize AR model for whitening, so we set max_p=5 and max_q=0.\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "### Step 3: Extracting and Visualizing Residuals\n",
    "By subtracting the \"stationary noise\" predicted by the model, we obtain the residuals $x_r = x - \\hat{x}$. This is the whitened data."
